															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1361261"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1344530432 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 Aug 2012 16:40</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1532458">
									

<p>I too greatly enjoy video and broadcast-style SCPs, and for that reason (in addition to the fact that it's executed well) I am giving this an upvote. However, I have a couple of nitpicks:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Addendum to Containment Procedures ██/██/20██: From this point forward, stop testing this thing on D-class subjects. We’ve wasted a dozen so far, and the only anomalous effect on them has been radiation poisoning. —O5-█</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This may be thing where I'm just trying to force my own headcanon, but I don't see why an O5 would get directly involved in something like that. This is a Safe-class object which, while lethal and disturbing, doesn't seem to represent an especially dire threat in relation to other SCPs, and I would think that the Research Director or perhaps even a Site Director would take care of this issue.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>When SCP-719-1 is in place, and SCP-719 is supplied power and turned on, SCP-719-1 will radiate electromagnetic radiation in various spectra including visible light, ultraviolet, [REDACTED], [REDACTED] and a substantial band in [REDACTED]. About 60% of emissions are ionizing radiation.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I have no idea what you're doing with the redactions here. Are there classified portions of the electromagnetic spectrum now or something? This, to me, was a dissonant note in an otherwise well-written article.</p>
<p>On the more positive side, I kind of like the fact that it's a &quot;Satanic&quot; cult, but not like some cheesy horror-movie style one.</p>
<p>Also:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>■External scenes will gradually become brighter, night becomes day, clouds vanish, and the sun— when visible— will grow progressively larger and whiter.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I don't know what your Photoshop skillz are like (mine are nonexistent or I would attempt it myself), but a picture in the article depicting this stage of the broadcast, IMHO, would look extremely badass and add a lot to the article.</p>
<p>Overall, good work.</p>

							</div>

								
					
